[{"id":"FT539977","type":"longtextV2","stimulusHtml":"Using the information in the pie charts above, identify two budgetary barriers that hinder the creation of new policy initiatives. Explain why each of the barriers you identified persists. Using your knowledge of United States politics, identify one nonbudgetary barrier AND explain how this barrier hinders the creation of new policy initiatives.","features":[{"type":"sharedpassage","html":"<img alt=\"Five pie graphs covering the years 1963, 1973, 1983, 1993 and 2003 are entitled, “Growth of Mandatory Spending in the Federal Budget,” each including a grey area of the circle labeled discretionary, a black area labeled entitlements, and a white area labeled net interest. For 1963 the grey area is 70.4%, the black is 22.7% and the white is 6.9%, with a total of 29.6% under the mandatory spending label. For 1973 the grey area is 55%, the black is 38% and the white is 7%, with a total of 45% under the mandatory spending label. For 1983 the grey area is 43.7%, the black is 45.2% and the white is 11.1%, with a total of 56.3% under the mandatory spending label. For 1993 the grey area is 38.6%, the black is 47.3% and the white is 14.1%, with a total of 61.4% under the mandatory spending label. For 2003 the grey area is 28%, the black is 58.2% and the white is 13.8%, with a projection total of 72% under the mandatory spending label.\" height=\"558\" src=\"https://assets.learnosity.com/organisations/537/media.academicmerit.com/0956111de497dc7c9a4e5539a43d8316/original.png\" width=\"667\">"}]}]